{"title_page": "Anna Buturlina", "text_new": "{{for|the Russian artist and noblewoman|Anna Artemevna Buturlina}}\n{{short description|Russian jazz singer and musical actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Anna Buturlina\n| image           = \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 WIKI F.png\n| caption         = Buturlina in 2018\n| birth_name      = Anna Vladimirovna Buturlina\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1977|5|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| genre = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation = Singer, theatre actress\n| instrument = vocals\n| years_active = 1996-present\n| associated_acts = \n}}\n\n'''Anna Vladimirovna Buturlina''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430}}, born 31 May 1977) is a [[Russia]]n jazz singer<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430|url=https://ucclub.ru/jazz/artists/buturlina/|accessdate=2018-07-25|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.muzklondike.ru/announc/289|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430: \"\u041d\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0433\u0443 \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043c\u0438\".|publisher=www.muzklondike.ru|accessdate=2018-03-23}}</ref> and musical actress.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0411\u043b\u0438\u0446-\u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u043d\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0443\u043d\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0430: \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430  \u043e \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u0438 \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0435|url=https://www.m24.ru/articles/dzhaz/19052016/105527|work=m24.ru|accessdate=2018-03-23|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nButurlina graduated from the music school named after [[Sergei Prokofiev]] in [[piano]]. Then she entered the Gnesin School of Music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meloman.ru/concert/letnij-dzhem-dlya-bolshoj-kompanii/|title=\"\u041b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438\". \u0417\u0432\u0451\u0437\u0434\u044b \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0430|publisher=www.meloman.ru|language=ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> In the third year of study at the conducting and choral department, Buturlin began to sing jazz and after graduating from school she entered [[Gnessin State Musical College]] in the pop-jazz department.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160612011523/http://kbanda.ru/index.php/muzyka/254-muzyka/5433-anna-buturlina-dzhazovoe-menshinstvo-tonet-v-massovoj-kulture \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u0414\u0436\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u00ab\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u00bb \u0442\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0435!]</ref> At the age of 19, she became a soloist of a big band under the management of [[Anatoly Kroll]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jazzmap.ru/rus/bands/Anna-Buturlina-vokal.php|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u043b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438, \u0431\u043b\u0438\u0436\u0430\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b, \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e, \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442, \u0412\u043e\u043a\u0430\u043b {{!}} Jazzmap.ru|publisher=www.jazzmap.ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\nButurlina toured<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0414\u0438\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434|url=https://ucclub.ru/event/08-12-2009/20-30/|accessdate=2018-06-21|language=ru}}</ref> with the Dixieland \"Moscow Ragtime Band\" and the big band RAM. Gnesinyh run by Vladimir Andreev. The singer's debut took place in December 1996 with the ensemble [[Ivan Farmakovsky]] at the Moscow Autumn Festival. In 1998, cooperation began with the ensemble \u201cJAZZ-ACCORD\u201d. November 23, 1998 in the studio RAM them. Gnesinyh made the first audio recording<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 - \"\u041e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e \"|url=https://newsmuz.com/news/2018/anna-buturlina-ostorozhno-40772|work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0448\u043e\u0443 \u0431\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430 \u0438 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 NEWSmuz.com|date=2018-03-31|accessdate=2018-06-21|language=ru}}</ref> with the ensemble \"Raznyye ludi\", which included the famous jazz standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penza-press.ru/lenta-novostey/129413/dzhejdi-volter-cel-muzykanta-privlech-lyudej-a-ne-otpugnut|title=\u0414\u0436\u0435\u0439\u0414\u0438 \u0423\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0435\u0440: \u0426\u0435\u043b\u044c \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430 - \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0447\u044c \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439, \u0430 \u043d\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043f\u0443\u0433\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044c \u2014 \u041f\u0435\u043d\u0437\u0430-\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441|publisher=www.penza-press.ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\nButurlina has recorded vocals for movies and cartoons. Her most iconic works are in [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] animation films,<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0437\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u043e\u0432|url=https://dni.ru/culture/2018/3/29/394595.html|work=\u0414\u043d\u0438 \u0440\u0443|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> where she voiced two princesses - [[Tiana (Disney)|Tiana]] (''[[The Princess and the Frog]]'') and [[Elsa (Disney)|Elsa]] (''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' and ''[[Frozen II]]''). She performed the Russian versions of the songs \"[[Let It Go (Disney song)|Let It Go]]\" from ''Frozen'' and \"[[Into the Unknown (Disney song)|Into the Unknown]]\" from ''Frozen II''.\n\nOn February 9, 2020, Buturlina was called to join [[Idina Menzel]], [[Aurora (singer)|Aurora]] and eight more of Elsa's international dubbers to perform the song \u201c[[Into the Unknown (Disney song)|Into the Unknown]]\u201d during the [[92nd Academy Awards]]. Every international performer sang one line of the song in a different language: [[Maria Lucia Rosenberg|Maria Lucia Heiberg Rosenberg]] in [[Danish language|Danish]], [[Willemijn Verkaik]] in [[German language|German]], [[Takako Matsu]] in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Carmen Sarah\u00ed]] in [[Spanish language in the Americas|Latin American Spanish]], [[Lisa Stokke]] in [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], [[Katarzyna \u0141aska|Kasia \u0141aska]] in [[Polish language|Polish]], Buturlina in [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Gisela (singer)|Gisela]] in [[Peninsular Spanish|European Spanish]] and [[Wichayanee Pearklin|Gam Wichayanee]] in [[Thai language|Thai]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/watch-idina-menzel-and-9-fellow-elsas-sing-frozen-2s-into-the-unknown-at-the-oscars|title=Watch Idina Menzel and 9 Fellow Elsas Sing Frozen 2's 'Into the Unknown' at the Oscars|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-02-10|website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nButurlina is married with two daughters,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.i-igrushki.ru/archive/anna-buturlina-chem-bolshe-lyubvi-vy-darite-tem-bolshe-eye-stanovitsya-.html|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u00ab\u0427\u0435\u043c \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u043b\u044e\u0431\u0432\u0438 \u0432\u044b \u0434\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435, \u0442\u0435\u043c \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u0435\u0451 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f!\u00bb - \"\u0418\u0433\u0440\u044b \u0438 \u0418\u0433\u0440\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\" \u21163-2018|publisher=www.i-igrushki.ru|language=ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womanhit.ru/stars/news/2018-05-11-kak-zvezdy-sezdili-namajskie-prazdniki/|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u044b \u043e\u0442\u0434\u043e\u0445\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432|publisher=www.womanhit.ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> Evdokia (2006) and Antonina (2016).<ref>[http://www.womanontop.ru/2012/06/anna-buturlina-printsessa-dzhaza/ \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430 \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Music albums ===\n* \"Black Coffee\", 2002\n* \u201cMy Favorite Songs\u201d, 2006\n* \u201cEverything is jazz\u201d, 2017\n* \"Caution \"music\"\",<ref>{{Cite news|title=\"\u041e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e \"\u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\"\" \u0410\u043d\u043d\u044b \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0438 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430|url=http://www.intermedia.ru/news/319222|date=2018-01-22|accessdate=2018-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://okultureno.ru/news/27166-anna-buturlina-prokommentirovala-vykhod-svoego-diska-na-firme-melodiya/|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0438\u0440\u043c\u0435 \"\u041c\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0438\u044f\" {{!}} \u041e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b|publisher=okultureno.ru|language=ru|accessdate=2018-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303051942/http://okultureno.ru/news/27166-anna-buturlina-prokommentirovala-vykhod-svoego-diska-na-firme-melodiya/|archive-date=2018-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> 2017\n* \"The key to the kingdom\",<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c \"\u041a\u043b\u044e\u0447 \u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\" \u0410\u043d\u043d\u044b \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 {{!}} JazzPeople|url=https://jazzpeople.ru/news/klyuch-ot-korolevstva-anny-buturlino/|work=JazzPeople|date=2018-01-16|accessdate=2018-03-02|language=ru-RU}}</ref> 2017\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buturlina, Anna}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Russian female singers]]\n[[Category:Russian jazz singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Russian jazz singer and musical actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{for|the Russian artist and noblewoman|Anna Artemevna Buturlina}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Anna Buturlina\n| image           = \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 WIKI F.png\n| caption         = Buturlina in 2018\n| birth_name      = Anna Vladimirovna Buturlina\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1977|5|31|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Moscow]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| genre = [[Jazz]]\n| occupation = Singer, theatre actress\n| instrument = vocals\n| years_active = 1996-present\n| associated_acts = \n}}\n\n'''Anna Vladimirovna Buturlina''' ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430}}, born 31 May 1977) is a [[Russia]]n jazz singer<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430|url=https://ucclub.ru/jazz/artists/buturlina/|accessdate=2018-07-25|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.muzklondike.ru/announc/289|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u00ab\u041d\u0435 \u043c\u043e\u0433\u0443 \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c\u0441\u044f \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u0432\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043c\u0438\u00bb.|publisher=www.muzklondike.ru|accessdate=2018-03-23}}</ref> and musical actress.<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0411\u043b\u0438\u0446-\u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u043d\u0430\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0443\u043d\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0430: \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430  \u043e \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u0438 \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0435|url=https://www.m24.ru/articles/dzhaz/19052016/105527|work=m24.ru|accessdate=2018-03-23|language=ru}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nButurlina graduated from the music school named after [[Sergei Prokofiev]] in [[piano]]. Then she entered the Gnesin School of Music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meloman.ru/concert/letnij-dzhem-dlya-bolshoj-kompanii/|title=\u00ab\u041b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438\u00bb. \u0417\u0432\u0451\u0437\u0434\u044b \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0430|publisher=www.meloman.ru|lang=ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> In the third year of study at the conducting and choral department, Buturlin began to sing jazz and after graduating from school she entered [[Gnessin State Musical College]] in the pop-jazz department.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20160612011523/http://kbanda.ru/index.php/muzyka/254-muzyka/5433-anna-buturlina-dzhazovoe-menshinstvo-tonet-v-massovoj-kulture \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u0414\u0436\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u00ab\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u00bb \u0442\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0435!]</ref> At the age of 19, she became a soloist of a big band under the management of [[Anatoly Kroll]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jazzmap.ru/rus/bands/Anna-Buturlina-vokal.php|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u043b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438, \u0431\u043b\u0438\u0436\u0430\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0442\u044b, \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e, \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442, \u0412\u043e\u043a\u0430\u043b {{!}} Jazzmap.ru|publisher=www.jazzmap.ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\nButurlina toured<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0414\u0438\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0434|url=https://ucclub.ru/event/08-12-2009/20-30/|accessdate=2018-06-21|language=ru}}</ref> with the Dixieland \"Moscow Ragtime Band\" and the big band RAM. Gnesinyh run by Vladimir Andreev. The singer's debut took place in December 1996 with the ensemble [[Ivan Farmakovsky]] at the Moscow Autumn Festival. In 1998, cooperation began with the ensemble \u201cJAZZ-ACCORD\u201d. November 23, 1998 in the studio RAM them. Gnesinyh made the first audio recording<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 - \u00ab\u041e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e \u00bb|url=https://newsmuz.com/news/2018/anna-buturlina-ostorozhno-40772|work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0448\u043e\u0443 \u0431\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0430 \u0438 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 NEWSmuz.com|date=2018-03-31|accessdate=2018-06-21|language=ru}}</ref> with the ensemble \"Raznyye ludi\", which included the famous jazz standard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.penza-press.ru/lenta-novostey/129413/dzhejdi-volter-cel-muzykanta-privlech-lyudej-a-ne-otpugnut|title=\u0414\u0436\u0435\u0439\u0414\u0438 \u0423\u043e\u043b\u0442\u0435\u0440: \u0426\u0435\u043b\u044c \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430 - \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043b\u0435\u0447\u044c \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439, \u0430 \u043d\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043f\u0443\u0433\u043d\u0443\u0442\u044c \u2014 \u041f\u0435\u043d\u0437\u0430-\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441|publisher=www.penza-press.ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>\n\nButurlina has recorded vocals for movies and cartoons. Her most iconic works are in [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] animation films<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0437\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0444\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043c\u043e\u0432|url=https://dni.ru/culture/2018/3/29/394595.html|work=\u0414\u043d\u0438 \u0440\u0443|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref>, where she voiced two princesses - [[Tiana (Disney)|Tiana]] (''[[The Princess and the Frog]]'') and [[Elsa (Disney)|Elsa]] (''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'' and ''[[Frozen II]]''). She performed the Russian versions of the songs \"[[Let It Go (Disney song)|Let It Go]]\" from ''Frozen'' and \"[[Into the Unknown (Disney song)|Into the Unknown]]\" from ''Frozen II''.\n\nOn February 9, 2020, Buturlina was called to join [[Idina Menzel]], [[Aurora (singer)|Aurora]] and eight more of Elsa's international dubbers to perform the song \u201c[[Into the Unknown (Disney song)|Into the Unknown]]\u201d during the [[92nd Academy Awards]]. Every international performer sang one line of the song in a different language: [[Maria Lucia Rosenberg|Maria Lucia Heiberg Rosenberg]] in [[Danish language|Danish]], [[Willemijn Verkaik]] in [[German language|German]], [[Takako Matsu]] in [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[Carmen Sarah\u00ed]] in [[Spanish language in the Americas|Latin American Spanish]], [[Lisa Stokke]] in [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]], [[Katarzyna \u0141aska|Kasia \u0141aska]] in [[Polish language|Polish]], Buturlina in [[Russian language|Russian]], [[Gisela (singer)|Gisela]] in [[Peninsular Spanish|European Spanish]] and [[Wichayanee Pearklin|Gam Wichayanee]] in [[Thai language|Thai]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/watch-idina-menzel-and-9-fellow-elsas-sing-frozen-2s-into-the-unknown-at-the-oscars|title=Watch Idina Menzel and 9 Fellow Elsas Sing Frozen 2's 'Into the Unknown' at the Oscars|last=McPhee|first=Ryan|date=2020-02-10|website=Playbill|language=en|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nButurlina is married with two daughters,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.i-igrushki.ru/archive/anna-buturlina-chem-bolshe-lyubvi-vy-darite-tem-bolshe-eye-stanovitsya-.html|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u00ab\u0427\u0435\u043c \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u043b\u044e\u0431\u0432\u0438 \u0432\u044b \u0434\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435, \u0442\u0435\u043c \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0435 \u0435\u0451 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f!\u00bb - \"\u0418\u0433\u0440\u044b \u0438 \u0418\u0433\u0440\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\" \u21163-2018|publisher=www.i-igrushki.ru|lang=ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.womanhit.ru/stars/news/2018-05-11-kak-zvezdy-sezdili-namajskie-prazdniki/|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u044b \u043e\u0442\u0434\u043e\u0445\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044f \u043c\u0430\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432|publisher=www.womanhit.ru|accessdate=2018-06-21}}</ref> Evdokia (2006) and Antonina (2016).<ref>[http://www.womanontop.ru/2012/06/anna-buturlina-printsessa-dzhaza/ \u041f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430 \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430]</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Music albums ===\n* \"Black Coffee\", 2002\n* \u201cMy Favorite Songs\u201d, 2006\n* \u201cEverything is jazz\u201d, 2017\n* \"Caution \"music\"\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u00ab\u041e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e \"\u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\"\u00bb \u0410\u043d\u043d\u044b \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0436\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u043e\u0432\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0434\u0436\u0430\u0437\u0430 \u0438 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430|url=http://www.intermedia.ru/news/319222|date=2018-01-22|accessdate=2018-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://okultureno.ru/news/27166-anna-buturlina-prokommentirovala-vykhod-svoego-diska-na-firme-melodiya/|title=\u0410\u043d\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u044b\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0438\u0440\u043c\u0435 \u00ab\u041c\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0438\u044f\u00bb {{!}} \u041e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b|publisher=okultureno.ru|lang=ru|accessdate=2018-03-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303051942/http://okultureno.ru/news/27166-anna-buturlina-prokommentirovala-vykhod-svoego-diska-na-firme-melodiya/|archive-date=2018-03-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>, 2017\n* \"The key to the kingdom\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0430\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c \u00ab\u041a\u043b\u044e\u0447 \u043e\u0442 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u00bb \u0410\u043d\u043d\u044b \u0411\u0443\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0439 {{!}} JazzPeople|url=https://jazzpeople.ru/news/klyuch-ot-korolevstva-anny-buturlino/|work=JazzPeople|date=2018-01-16|accessdate=2018-03-02|language=ru-RU}}</ref>, 2017\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buturlina, Anna}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Moscow]]\n[[Category:Russian female singers]]\n[[Category:Russian jazz singers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anna_Buturlina"}
{"title_page": "Andy Panayi", "text_new": "[[File:Apanayi.jpg|right|thumb|Andy Panayi]]\n\n'''Andy Panayi''' is a British [[jazz]] [[musician]], skilled in performance, [[Musical composition|composition]] and [[arranging]]. He plays all the [[flute]]s and all the [[saxophone]]s and leads a selection of jazz and [[Classical music|classical]] groups. He also writes [[Commission (art)|commissioned]] works and self commissioned work for his own arranging, composing & transcribing business ALP Music.\n\n== British Jazz Scene ==\nBorn in [[Islington]] in north [[London]] and interested in music from an early age, Andy studied at the [[Trinity College of Music]] before embarking on a professional music career.\n\nAndy is a leading member of the [[United Kingdom|British]] jazz scene having performed and [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] with a selection of artists including [[Shirley Bassey]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[Salena Jones]] and [[Helen Shapiro]].\n\nHe's also worked alongside or supported many other leading musicians and groups including The [[Moscow]] City [[Ballet]], [[Ronnie Scott]] & his Side-men, [[BBC Big Band]], [[John Dankworth]] and [[Cleo Laine]], [[Humphrey Lyttelton]], [[Suzi Quatro]],<ref name=FirstNight /> and others.\n\nHe now works with the [[Associated Board of the Royal Schools of Music]] (ABRSM) as a consultant specialising in developing the Jazz syllabus for future examinations.\n\n== Awards ==\n\nPanayi has won several awards during his career including; The [[Marty Paich]] Arranging Award, The [[John Dankworth]] Soloist Award, The [[Worshipful Company of Musicians]] Jazz Medal, British Jazz Awards for [[Jazz]] [[Flute]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n* ''[[Annie Get Your Gun - 1986 London Cast]]'' - plays woodwinds in the album from the first London revival of [[Irving Berlin#\"Annie Get Your Gun\" (1946)|Irving Berlin]]'s musical ''[[Annie Get Your Gun (musical)|Annie Get Your Gun]]'', starring Suzi Quatro as [[Annie Oakley]] and [[Eric Flynn]] as [[Frank E. Butler|Frank Butler]]<ref name=FirstNight>\n{{cite web\n  | title = First Night Records Online Store, Annie Get Your Gun - 1986 London Cast\n  | work = first-night-records.co.uk\n  | publisher = First Night Records\n  | location = London, United Kingdom\n  | url = http://first-night-records.co.uk/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=87\n  | accessdate = 10 June 2012\n}}</ref>\n* \"News from Blueport\" - The Andy Panayi [[Quartet]] plays a tribute to [[Gerry Mulligan]]\n* \"Uschi's House\" - Flux ([[Latin]] Jazz/House music CD) playing flutes & saxes\n* \"Blown Away\" -The Andy Panayi Quartet - on [[Ronnie Scott's]] Jazz House A top 10 album of the year in the Jazz Journal of 2001\n* \"Whooeeee\" - The Andy Panayi Quartet - on Mainstem Records featured as CD OF THE WEEK in [[The Observer]].\n* \"Time Displaced\" - The Andy Panayi Jazz Flute - on Mainstem Records featured as CD OF THE WEEK in The Observer.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.andypanayi.co.uk/ Andy Panayi's internet pages]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Panayi, Andy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Apanayi.jpg|right|thumb|Andy Panayi]]\n\n'''Andy Panayi''' is a British [[jazz]] [[musician]], skilled in performance, [[Musical composition|composition]] and [[arranging]]. He plays all the [[flute]]s and all the [[saxophone]]s and leads a selection of jazz and [[Classical music|classical]] groups. He also writes [[Commission (art)|commissioned]] works and self commissioned work for his own arranging, composing & transcribing business ALP Music.\n\n== British Jazz Scene ==\nBorn in [[Islington]] in north [[London]] and interested in music from an early age, Andy studied at the [[Trinity College of Music]] before embarking on a professional music career.\n\nAndy is a leading member of the [[United Kingdom|British]] jazz scene having performed and [[Sound recording and reproduction|recorded]] with a selection of artists including [[Shirley Bassey]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[Salena Jones]] and [[Helen Shapiro]].\n\nHe's also worked alongside or supported many other leading musicians and groups including The [[Moscow]] City [[Ballet]], [[Ronnie Scott]] & his Side-men, [[BBC Big Band]], [[John Dankworth]] and [[Cleo Laine]], [[Humphrey Lyttelton]], [[Suzi Quatro]],<ref name=FirstNight /> and others.\n\nHe now works with the [[Associated Board of the Royal Schools of Music]] (ABRSM) as a consultant specialising in developing the Jazz syllabus for future examinations.\n\n== Awards ==\n\nPanayi has won several awards during his career including; The [[Marty Paich]] Arranging Award, The [[John Dankworth]] Soloist Award, The [[Worshipful Company of Musicians]] Jazz Medal, British Jazz Awards for [[Jazz]] [[Flute]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n* ''[[Annie Get Your Gun - 1986 London Cast]]'' - plays woodwinds in the album from the first London revival of [[Irving Berlin#\"Annie Get Your Gun\" (1946)|Irving Berlin]]'s musical ''[[Annie Get Your Gun (musical)|Annie Get Your Gun]]'', starring Suzi Quatro as [[Annie Oakley]] and [[Eric Flynn]] as [[Frank E. Butler|Frank Butler]]<ref name=FirstNight>\n{{cite web\n  | title = First Night Records Online Store, Annie Get Your Gun - 1986 London Cast\n  | work = first-night-records.co.uk\n  | publisher = First Night Records\n  | location = London, United Kingdom\n  | url = http://first-night-records.co.uk/catalog/product_info.php?products_id=87\n  | accessdate = 10 June 2012\n}}</ref>\n* \"News from Blueport\" - The Andy Panayi [[Quartet]] plays a tribute to [[Gerry Mulligan]]\n* \"Uschi's House\" - Flux ([[Latin]] Jazz/House music CD) playing flutes & saxes\n* \"Blown Away\" -The Andy Panayi Quartet - on [[Ronnie Scott's]] Jazz House A top 10 album of the year in the Jazz Journal of 2001\n* \"Whooeeee\" - The Andy Panayi Quartet - on Mainstem Records featured as CD OF THE WEEK in [[The Observer]].\n* \"Time Displaced\" - The Andy Panayi Jazz Flute - on Mainstem Records featured as CD OF THE WEEK in The Observer.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.andypanayi.co.uk/ Andy Panayi's internet pages]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Panayi, Andy}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British jazz flautists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_Panayi"}
{"title_page": "Yoshihiro Senda", "text_new": "[[File:\u5343\u7530\u5609\u535a\uff08\u64ae\u5f71\uff1a\u7560\u4e2d\u548c\u4e45\u6c0f\uff09.jpg|alt=A headshot of Yoshihiro Senda.|thumb|Yoshihiro Senda (Photo by Kazuhisa Hatanaka)]]\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yoshihiro Senda'''|\u5343\u7530 \u5609\u535a|Senda Yoshihiro|extra=born July 19, 1963}}<ref>\u300e\u8aad\u58f2\u5e74\u9451 2016\u5e74\u7248\u300f\uff08[[Yomiuri Shimbun|\u8aad\u58f2\u65b0\u805e]]\u6771\u4eac\u672c\u793e\u30012016\u5e74\uff09p.264</ref><ref name=\"nara-univ_20140224\">{{Cite press release|url=http://www.nara-u.ac.jp/news/topic/detail.php?id=1240|date=2014-02-24|title=\u6b21\u671f\u5b66\u9577\u306e\u9078\u51fa\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066|publisher=[[Nara University]]|accessdate=2016-12-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514115849/http://www.nara-u.ac.jp/news/topic/detail.php?id=1240|archivedate=2014-05-14}}</ref> is a [[Japan]]ese [[Archaeology|castle archeologist]]. He is a professor at [[Nara University]] and was president of the university from April 2014 to August 2016. His work focuses on the excavation and maintenance of castles from medieval and modern Japan, as well as comparative studies of castles around the world including those in Europe and [[Mongolia]]. He received the Hamada Seiry\u014d Prize in 2015. He worked as a historical consultant for the [[taiga drama]] ''[[Sanada Maru]]'' in 2016. He has made several appearances on television. His books include ''Nobunaga's Castles'', published by [[Iwanami Shoten]].\n\n== Biography ==\nYoshihiro Senda was born in [[Aichi Prefecture]]. He entered Nara University in 1982 and graduated in 1986. Afterwards, he became a curator at Nagoya City Miharashidai Archeological Museum. In 1990, he became an assistant at the [[National Museum of Japanese History]]. In 1995, he studied at the [[German Archaeological Institute|German Archeological Institute]] and the [[University of York]] in the United Kingdom as an overseas researcher for the Ministry of Education, Science and Culture. In 2000, he received a [[Doctor of Letters]] from [[Osaka University]] for his book ''The Construction of Shokuh[[Chikuma Shob\u014d|\u014d]] Castles''. In 2001, he worked as assistant professor for the Archeology Division of the National Museum of Japanese History. In 2005, he became associate professor at Nara University and professor in 2009. He served as guest professor at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]] and the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt University]] from August 2012 until August 2013. He acted as president of Nara University from 2014 until 2016. He was awarded the Hamada Seiryo Prize in 2015 by the city of [[Kishiwada, Osaka|Kishiwada]] and [[The Asahi Shimbun|Asahi Shimbun]] for his contributions to and breakthroughs in the field of archeology of castles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.kishiwada.osaka.jp/soshiki/70/hama-sei.html|title=Hamada Seiryo Prize - List of Past Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Kishiwada City Official Site|language=Japanese|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> In 2016, Senda worked on the researched-based historical reconstruction of the [[Sanada Maru]] for the NHK's [[taiga drama]] ''[[Sanada Maru (TV series)|Sanada Maru]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nara-u.ac.jp/news/2016/60|title=\u672c\u5b66\u6587\u5b66\u90e8\u306e\u5343\u7530\u5609\u535a\u6559\u6388\u304cNHK\u5927\u6cb3\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u300c\u771f\u7530\u4e38\u300d\u3067\u771f\u7530\u4e38\u306e\u5fa9\u5143\u8003\u8a3c\u3092\u62c5\u5f53\uff01|last=|first=|date=September 15, 2016|website=Nara University Official Site|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> He appeared in the NHK's programs ''Historical Anecdotes'' and ''Shumi Doki! Oshiro he Ikou!'' The head of the NHK Osaka Broadcasting Center expressed gratitude to Senda for improving the programs' quality by providing castle knowledge and insights in an easy to understand manner. In 2018, the Nara Newspaper awarded him the Nara Newspaper Culture Award and the city of [[Uto, Kumamoto|Uto]], Kumamoto Prefecture honored him for his contributions to the city.\n\n== Published Work ==\n\n* ''{{nihongo|Construction of Shokuh\u014d Castles|\u7e54\u8c4a\u7cfb\u57ce\u90ed\u306e\u5f62\u6210}}''. [[University of Tokyo Press]]\uff0c2000.\n* ''{{nihongo|A Walk through Sengoku Period Castles|\u6226\u56fd\u306e\u57ce\u3092\u6b69\u304f}}''. [[Chikuma Shob\u014d]], 2003.\n* ''{{nihongo|[[Nobunaga Oda|Nobunaga]]'s Castles|\u4fe1\u9577\u306e\u57ce}}''. [[Iwanami New books]], 2013.\n* ''{{nihongo|Mysteries of the [[Sanada Maru]]: Understanding the Sengoku Period through Castles|\u771f\u7530\u4e38\u306e\u8b0e\u3000\u6226\u56fd\u6642\u4ee3\u3092\u300c\u57ce\u300d\u3067\u8aad\u307f\u89e3\u304f}}''. [[NHK publication new books]], 2015.\n* ''{{nihongo|[[Sanada Yukimura|Sanada Nobushige]]'s Path to Victory|\u771f\u7530\u4fe1\u7e41\u300c\u52dd\u5229\u300d\u3078\u306e\u6761\u4ef6}}''. [[Mikasa Publishing]], 2015.\n\n===Co-authored===\n* ''{{nihongo|Castles and the Unification of Japan|\u5929\u4e0b\u7d71\u4e00\u3068\u57ce}}'', [[National Museum of Japanese History]], Plan exhibition display pictorial record (compilation) ''[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]'', 2000\n\n== Public Activities ==\n* Contributed to the ''Asu he no Wadai'' column in [[The Nikkei|Nihon Keizai Shimbun]]'s evening paper from July to December 2016.\n* Assisted in the excavation and maintenance of castles in various locales, helped protect cultural property, and helped compile histories of local governments. Has been a member of the committee responsible for selecting [[Japan's Top 100 Castles]] as well as the [[Continued Top 100 Japanese Castles]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Castle]]\n* [[Archaeology]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Twitter|id=yoshi_nara}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senda, Yoshihiro}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People from Nagoya]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese archaeologists]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:\u5343\u7530\u5609\u535a\uff08\u64ae\u5f71\uff1a\u7560\u4e2d\u548c\u4e45\u6c0f\uff09.jpg|alt=A headshot of Yoshihiro Senda.|thumb|Yoshihiro Senda (Photo by Kazuhisa Hatanaka)]]\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yoshihiro Senda'''|\u5343\u7530 \u5609\u535a|Senda Yoshihiro|extra=born July 19, 1963}}<ref>\u300e\u8aad\u58f2\u5e74\u9451 2016\u5e74\u7248\u300f\uff08[[Yomiuri Shimbun|\u8aad\u58f2\u65b0\u805e]]\u6771\u4eac\u672c\u793e\u30012016\u5e74\uff09p.264</ref><ref name=\"nara-univ_20140224\">{{Cite press release|url=http://www.nara-u.ac.jp/news/topic/detail.php?id=1240|date=2014-02-24|title=\u6b21\u671f\u5b66\u9577\u306e\u9078\u51fa\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066|publisher=[[Nara University]]|accessdate=2016-12-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514115849/http://www.nara-u.ac.jp/news/topic/detail.php?id=1240|archivedate=2014-05-14}}</ref> is a [[Japan]]ese [[Archaeology|castle archeologist]]. He is a professor at [[Nara University]] and was president of the university from April 2014 to August 2016. His work focuses on the excavation and maintenance of castles from medieval and modern Japan, as well as comparative studies of castles around the world including those in Europe and [[Mongolia]]. He received the Hamada Seiry\u014d Prize in 2015. He worked as a historical consultant for the [[taiga drama]] ''[[Sanada Maru]]'' in 2016. He has made several appearances on television. His books include ''Nobunaga's Castles'', published by [[Iwanami Shoten]].\n\n== Biography ==\nYoshihiro Senda was born in [[Aichi Prefecture]]. He entered Nara University in 1982 and graduated in 1986. Afterwards, he became a curator at Nagoya City Miharashidai Archeological Museum. In 1990, he became an assistant at the [[National Museum of Japanese History]]. In 1995, he studied at the [[German Archaeological Institute|German Archeological Institute]] and the [[University of York]] in the United Kingdom as an overseas researcher for the Ministry of Education, Science and Culture. In 2000, he received a [[Doctor of Letters]] from [[Osaka University]] for his book ''The Construction of Shokuh[[Chikuma Shob\u014d|\u014d]] Castles''. In 2001, he worked as assistant professor for the Archeology Division of the National Museum of Japanese History. In 2005, he became associate professor at Nara University and professor in 2009. He served as guest professor at the [[University of T\u00fcbingen]] and the [[Goethe University Frankfurt|Frankfurt University]] from August 2012 until August 2013. He acted as president of Nara University from 2014 until 2016. He was awarded the Hamada Seiryo Prize in 2015 by the city of [[Kishiwada, Osaka|Kishiwada]] and [[The Asahi Shimbun|Asahi Shimbun]] for his contributions to and breakthroughs in the field of archeology of castles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.city.kishiwada.osaka.jp/soshiki/70/hama-sei.html|title=Hamada Seiryo Prize - List of Past Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Kishiwada City Official Site|language=Japanese|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> In 2016, Senda worked on the researched-based historical reconstruction of the [[Sanada Maru]] for the NHK's [[taiga drama]] ''[[Sanada Maru (TV series)|Sanada Maru]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nara-u.ac.jp/news/2016/60|title=\u672c\u5b66\u6587\u5b66\u90e8\u306e\u5343\u7530\u5609\u535a\u6559\u6388\u304cNHK\u5927\u6cb3\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u300c\u771f\u7530\u4e38\u300d\u3067\u771f\u7530\u4e38\u306e\u5fa9\u5143\u8003\u8a3c\u3092\u62c5\u5f53\uff01|last=|first=|date=September 15, 2016|website=Nara University Official Site|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> He appeared in the NHK's programs ''Historical Anecdotes'' and ''Shumi Doki! Oshiro he Ikou!'' The head of the NHK Osaka Broadcasting Center expressed gratitude to Senda for improving the programs' quality by providing castle knowledge and insights in an easy to understand manner. In 2018, the Nara Newspaper awarded him the Nara Newspaper Culture Award and the city of [[Uto, Kumamoto|Uto]], Kumamoto Prefecture honored him for his contributions to the city.\n\n== Writings ==\n\n* ''{{nihongo|Construction of Shokuh\u014d Castles|\u7e54\u8c4a\u7cfb\u57ce\u90ed\u306e\u5f62\u6210}}''. [[University of Tokyo Press]]\uff0c2000.\n* ''{{nihongo|A Walk through Sengoku Period Castles|\u6226\u56fd\u306e\u57ce\u3092\u6b69\u304f}}''. [[Chikuma Shob\u014d]], 2003.\n* ''{{nihongo|[[Nobunaga Oda|Nobunaga]]'s Castles|\u4fe1\u9577\u306e\u57ce}}''. [[Iwanami New books]], 2013.\n* ''{{nihongo|Mysteries of the [[Sanada Maru]]: Understanding the Sengoku Period through Castles|\u771f\u7530\u4e38\u306e\u8b0e\u3000\u6226\u56fd\u6642\u4ee3\u3092\u300c\u57ce\u300d\u3067\u8aad\u307f\u89e3\u304f}}''. [[NHK publication new books]], 2015.\n* ''{{nihongo|[[Sanada Yukimura|Sanada Nobushige]]'s Path to Victory|\u771f\u7530\u4fe1\u7e41\u300c\u52dd\u5229\u300d\u3078\u306e\u6761\u4ef6}}''. [[Mikasa Publishing]], 2015.\n\n===Co-authored===\n* ''{{nihongo|Castles and the Unification of Japan|\u5929\u4e0b\u7d71\u4e00\u3068\u57ce}}'', [[National Museum of Japanese History]], Plan exhibition display pictorial record (compilation) ''[[Yomiuri Shimbun]]'', 2000\n\n== Public Activities ==\n* Contributed to the ''Asu he no Wadai'' column in [[The Nikkei|Nihon Keizai Shimbun]]'s evening paper from July to December 2016.\n* Assisted in the excavation and maintenance of castles in various locales, helped protect cultural property, and helped compile histories of local governments. Has been a member of the committee responsible for selecting [[Japan's Top 100 Castles]] as well as the [[Continued Top 100 Japanese Castles]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Castle]]\n* [[Archaeology]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Twitter|id=yoshi_nara}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Senda, Yoshihiro}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:People from Nagoya]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese archaeologists]]\n", "name_user": "Erynamrod", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWritings:adjusted title name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoshihiro_Senda"}
{"title_page": "Monaco Telecom", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Monaco Telecom\t\n| logo = Monaco Telecom logo.svg\n| caption =\n| type = Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Anonyme Mon\u00e9gasque (SAM)\n| fate =\n| traded_as =\n| predecessor = Office Mon\u00e9gasque des T\u00e9l\u00e9phones\n| successor =\n| foundation = 1997\n| founder = \n| defunct =\n| location  = [[Monaco]]\n| locations =\n| area_served = \n| key_people = Etienne Franzi<br>{{small|(Chairman of the Board)}}<br>Martin P\u00e9ronnet<br>{{small|(CEO)}}\n| industry = Telecommunications\n| products = \n| services =\n| net_income = 52.1 million euros (2015)\n| revenue = 149.9 million euros (2015)\n| operating_income = \n| aum =\n| owner = [[Xavier Niel]]<ref>http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/04/25/uk-cable-wirlss-idUKBREA3O0IS20140425</ref>\n| num_employees = 226\n| parent =\n| divisions =\n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|http://www.monaco-telecom.mc/}}\n}}\n\n'''Monaco Telecom''' is the main [[telecommunications provider]] in the [[Principality of Monaco]]. The company was founded in 1997 following a decision by the [[government of Monaco]] to privatize the state-owned Office Mon\u00e9gasque des T\u00e9l\u00e9phones.\n[[File:Monaco Telecom Boutique.jpg|thumb|Monaco Telecom store]]\n\n==International development==\n===Africa===\nIn August 2012, Monaco Telecom sold its stake in its subsidiary, Afinis Communications - a Casablanca, [[Morocco]]-based telecommunications provider serving Africa's largest corporations - to SkyVision. In September of the same year, the Planor/Kome CESSE/Monaco Telecom consortium was awarded [[Mali]]'s third mobile telephone licence. Monaco Telecom is the technical partner in the consortium, which operates through the Malian company, Alpha Telecom Mali.\n\n===Asia===\nMonaco Telecom holds a 36.37% stake in Roshan, [[Afghanistan]]'s leading telecommunications provider, and is the technical lead for the deployment of the Roshan's mobile-telephone network in Afghanistan. Deployment of the network was completed in July 2003. In Afghanistan, which is currently undergoing massive reconstruction, Monaco Telecom also offers a range of complementary telecommunications services, including ISP data networks, leased lines, call centres, and emergency numbers. Monaco Telecom also has an office in Dubai, in the United Arab Emirates.\n\n===Europe===\n'''Cyprus''': \nSince 2018, Monaco Telecom owns 'epic' (formerly MTN Cyprus) which is one of the largest telecommunication providers in [[Cyprus]] with a recorded share of broadband access at 47.8% in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=MTN moves forward with \u2018epic\u2019 change: 5G contender hits the ground running less than a year after take over|url=https://knews.kathimerini.com.cy/en/business/mtn-moves-forward-with-%E2%80%98epic-change |publisher=Kathimerini.com.cy |date=5 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Monaco Telecom to acquire MTN Cyprus |url=https://www.stockwatch.com.cy/en/article/tilepikoinonies/monaco-telecom-acquire-mtn-cyprus |publisher=Stockwatch Cyprus |date=16 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MTN Cyprus Sale to Monaco Telecom Completed|url=http://www.goldnews.com.cy/en/financial-services/mtn-cyprus-sale-to-monaco-telecom-completed |publisher=Gold News Cyprus |date=5 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Monaco Telecom acquires MTN Cyprus|url=https://www.hellomonaco.com/news/latest-news/monaco-telecom-acquires-mtn-cyprus/ |publisher=Hello Monaco |date=5 September 2018}}</ref> Epic provides integrated mobile and fixed telephony, internet and pay-TV services as well as specialised ICT solutions for businesses. It currently operates 18 stores with tech products, accessories and telecommunication solutions across all major cities.<ref>{{cite web |title=Telco MTN re-brands as epic|url=https://www.cyprusprofile.com/en/articles/telco-mtn-rebrands-as-epic/ |publisher=Cyprus Profile |date=18 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=MTN rebrands as epic|url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2019/06/20/mtn-rebrands-as-epic/ |publisher=Cyprus Mail |date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Kosovo''':\nMonaco Telecom won a 1999 United Nations contract to deploy and extend the [[Post and Telecom of Kosovo|Kosovo Telecom]] GSM network in [[Kosovo]]. Today, the mobile network covers over 99% of the population, with more than 1.2 million subscribers. In 2012 the Kosovo mobile telephony contract was extended for a further 3 years.\n\n'''Malta''': In December 2019, Monaco Telecom agreed to acquire [[Vodafone Malta]] for a cash consideration equivalent to an enterprise value of \u20ac250 million;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/vodafone-malta-on-sale-for-250-million.758248|title=Deal reached to sell Vodafone Malta for \u20ac250 million|website=Times of Malta|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref> the acquisition was accomplished on 31st March 2020.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|language=fr, en|url=https://www.monaco-telecom.mc/images/presse/CP_Malte_FR_UK.pdf|format=pdf|title=Monaco Telecom devient le premier op\u00e9rateur mobile \u00e0 Malte \u2013 Monaco Telecom becomes first mobile operator in Malta|date=2020-03-31|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"VF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.vodafone.com/news-and-media/vodafone-group-releases/news/vodafone-completes-sale-of-vodafone-malta|title=Vodafone completes sale of Vodafone Malta|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"ToM-2\">{{cite news|url=https://timesofmalta.com/articles/view/monaco-telecom-completes-250m-buyout-of-vodafone-malta.782477|title=Monaco Telecom completes \u20ac250m buyout of Vodafone Malta|work=[[Times of Malta]]|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref name=\"TMI\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2020-04-01/business-news/Monaco-Telecom-completes-Vodafone-Malta-acquisition-6736221518|title=Monaco Telecom completes Vodafone Malta acquisition|work=[[The Malta Independent]]|date=2020-04-01|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n'''Monaco''':\nMonaco Telecom offers Monegasque residents and companies the entire range of products and services expected of a major telecommunications company. Through a concession agreement with Principality, the company holds the monopoly for [[Landline|fixed-line telephone services]], internet access and television services while the mobile telephony market is entirely open to competition. Monaco Telecom currently owns and operates 5 sales outlets in Monaco.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Sector !! Number of customers\n|-\n| Fixed lines || 20 831\n|-\n| Mobile lines || 35 506 \n|-\n| Internet access || 18 096\n|-\n| TV || 13 829\n|-\n| 4 Play || 3 402\n|}\n\n==OnAir Communications==\nSince 2006, Monaco Telecom has been providing [[OnAir (telecommunications)|OnAir]] with infrastructure enabling in-flight connectivity\u2014via GSM and IP networks\u2014on several [[Airbus]] aircraft. In June 2006, OnAir extended its agreement with Monaco Telecom to include the development and management of its entire land-based network supporting GSM and GPRS calls originating from anywhere in the world. The first in-flight tests, on a commercial flight, were conducted in December 2007. By the end of 2011, the OnAir system was available in about a hundred aircraft operated by about fifteen companies.\nIn June 2010, Monaco Telecom and OnAir broadened their range of services to include a new offer OnMarine extending the maritime communications network.\n\n==Research and development==\nMonaco Telecom is a member of [[Eurecom]], an engineering school and communication systems research centre based in Sophia Antipolis, France.\n\n==Shareholders==\nMonaco Telecom is 55% owned by [[Xavier Niel]], founder and largest shareholder of the [[Paris]] based [[Iliad SA]]. The [[Monaco|principality of Monaco]] owns the remaining 45% through the wholly owned Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Nationale de Financement.<ref>http://www.universfreebox.com/article/25583/Xavier-Niel-rachete-55-de-Monaco-Telecom-le-gouvernement-monegasque-satisfait</ref>\n\n==Key dates==\n* '''2020''' : On 31st March Monaco Telecom acquires [[Vodafone Malta]].<ref name=\"MT\" /><ref name=\"VF\" /><ref name=\"ToM-2\" /><ref name=\"TMI\" />\n* '''2019''' : On 9 July Monaco Telecom launched its [[5G]] network in conjunction with the presentation of the commercial offer.<ref>{{Cite news|language=it|url=http://www.ansa.it/sito/notizie/tecnologia/tlc/2019/07/11/huawei-rete-5g-nel-principato-di-monaco_33bc4d3b-8ea3-47d0-bde2-ae21a001aac6.html|title=Huawei, rete 5G nel Principato di Monaco|work=[[Agenzia Nazionale Stampa Associata|ANSA]]|date=11 July 2019|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/115150/20190711/monaco-telecom-rolls-out-full-5g-coverage-using-huawei-gear-in-european-first.htm|title=Monaco Telecom Rolls Out Full 5G Coverage Using Huawei Gear In European First|author=Charleston Lim|work=Business Times (China)|location=[[Beijing]]|date=11 July 2019|accessdate=11 July 2019}}</ref> Within the same year the company has re-branded its MTN acquisition in Cyprus as epic<ref>{{cite web |title=MTN Cyprus rebrands as Epic|url=https://www.telecompaper.com/news/mtn-cyprus-rebrands-as-epic--1298379 |publisher=Telecom Paper |date=18 June 2019}}</ref>\n* '''2018''' : On 16 July Monaco Telecom acquires MTN Cyprus.<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-07-16/mtn-sells-cyprus-unit-to-monaco-telecom-for-260-million-euros</ref>\n* '''2015''' : On 8 September Monaco Telecom launched the ultra high speed broadband service using DOSCIS 3.0. Speed reaches 1Gbit down and 200Mbit up.\n:: Launch of LTE advanced in Monaco.\n::  Introduction of a new logo and a new visual identity.\n* '''2014''' : Acquisition of Monaco Telecom by [[Xavier Niel]],<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/04/25/cable-wirlss-idUSASM0006F320140425</ref> (founder and majority shareholder of the French Internet service provider and Mobile operator Iliad trading under the Free brand)\n::  African group Azur Telecom chose Monaco Telecom to accompany him in his development.<ref>http://economie.jeuneafrique.com/regions/afrique-subsaharienne/22242-azur-mise-sur-monaco-telecom-pour-decoller.html</ref>   \n* '''2013''' : Monaco Telecom and global carrier Level 3 signed a strategic agreement for international connectivity\n::  Launch of LTE in Monaco. \n* '''2012''' : the Planor/Kome CESSE/Monaco Telecom consortium was awarded Mali's third mobile telephone licence.\n::Monaco Telecom sold its stake in its subsidiary Afinis Communications to SkyVision.\n::Kosovo mobile-telephony contract extended for a further 3 years.\n* '''2011''' : Monaco Telecom launches its 4G LTE pilot service.\n::  Provides circuit-wide WiFi coverage for the Monaco Formula 1 Grand Prix.\n::Education & Research: Eurecom names its future Class of 2011-2012, \"Monaco Telecom\".\n::The ''Open des Artistes de Monaco'' art competition: artists' contributions illustrate the telephone directory of the Principality.\n::Monaco Telecom and Cable&Wireless Communications announce the formation of Afinis Communications, following the merger of Divona's and Connecteo's sales operation.\n* '''2010''' : OnAir and Monaco Telecom launch OnMarine, an extended maritime communications service.\n::Monaco Telecom partners with Eurecom.\n::Launches 30MB high-speed broadband and full digital TV services.\n* '''2009''' : Outdoor demonstration of mobile WiMax technology in Monaco.\n::Martin P\u00e9ronnet appointed as CEO (January 5, 2009).\n* '''2008''' : Monaco Telecom sells 60% of its stake in its call centre, eCALL.\n::Acquires Connecteo, a VDI service provider with operations in 6 African countries.\n::CWI selects Monaco Telecom to establish its first mobile WiMax Centre of Excellence, in partnership with Alvarion, Cisco and Nokia.\n* '''2007''' : Monaco Telecom unifies its four core service offerings (landline and mobile telephony, internet and television) under the Monaco Telecom brand, and changes its corporate visual identity.\n* '''2006''' : Monaco Telecom opens an office in Dubai.\n* '''2005''' : OnAir selects Monaco Telecom for its land-based infrastructure (in-flight GSM telephony services).\n* '''2004''' : U.K.-based Cable & Wireless International buys Vivendi Telecom International's stake in Monaco Telecom.\n::Monaco Telecom sets up two satellite telecommunications subsidiaries in the Maghreb: Tunisia-based Divona Telecom and Divona in Algeria.\n* '''2003''' : Signs mobile network management services agreement with Afghanistan-based Roshan.\n* '''1999''' : Awarded mobile network management services contract in Kosovo.\n::Vivendi Telecom International acquires 51% stake in Monaco Telecom.\n* '''1997''' : Government of Monaco privatizes Office Mon\u00e9gasque des T\u00e9l\u00e9phones and forms Monaco Telecom.\n* '''1996''' : The Principality of Monaco assigned its own country calling code (377).\n* '''1994''' : GSM network deployed in the Principality.\n* '''1890''' : First public telephones in the Principality of Monaco.\n\n==Corporate responsibility==\nFor several years Monaco Telecom has spearheaded initiatives to measure electromagnetic field intensities to reassure the public that its installations do not pose a health risk. As of November 2010, electromagnetic wave emissions are regulated under Monegasque legislation, itself inspired by the most stringent regulations in the industry, i.e., an electric-field intensity threshold of 6 Volts/metre for radio antenna, television, walkie-talkie, and WiFi emissions, and 4 Volts/metre for mobile-telephone relay antennas. Compliance with threshold values is monitored by the government-run DCE (Direction des Communications Electroniques) during annual measurement campaigns, or whenever new mobile radio frequency emitting equipment is brought into service.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.monaco-telecom.mc/}}\n\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of Europe]]\n[[Category:Communications in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1997]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Monaco Telecom\t\n| logo = Monaco Telecom logo.svg\n| caption =\n| type = Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 Anonyme Mon\u00e9gasque (SAM)\n| fate =\n| traded_as =\n| predecessor = Office Mon\u00e9gasque des T\u00e9l\u00e9phones\n| successor =\n| foundation = 1997\n| founder = \n| defunct =\n| location  = [[Monaco]]\n| locations =\n| area_served = \n| key_people = Etienne Franzi<br>{{small|(Chairman of the Board)}}<br>Martin P\u00e9ronnet<br>{{small|(CEO)}}\n| industry = Telecommunications\n| products = \n| services =\n| net_income = 52.1 million euros (2015)\n| revenue = 149.9 million euros (2015)\n| operating_income = \n| aum =\n| owner = [[Xavier Niel]]<ref>http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/04/25/uk-cable-wirlss-idUKBREA3O0IS20140425</ref>\n| num_employees = 226\n| parent =\n| divisions =\n| subsid = \n| homepage = {{url|http://www.monaco-telecom.mc/}}\n}}\n\n'''Monaco Telecom''' is the main [[telecommunications provider]] in the [[Principality of Monaco]]. The company was founded in 1997 following a decision by the [[government of Monaco]] to privatize the state-owned Office Mon\u00e9gasque des T\u00e9l\u00e9phones.\n[[File:Monaco Telecom Boutique.jpg|thumb|Monaco Telecom store]]\n\n==International development==\n===Africa===\nIn August 2012, Monaco Telecom sold its stake in its subsidiary, Afinis Communications - a Casablanca, [[Morocco]]-based telecommunications provider serving Africa's largest corporations - to SkyVision. In September of the same year, the Planor/Kome CESSE/Monaco Telecom consortium was awarded [[Mali]]'s third mobile telephone licence. Monaco Telecom is the technical partner in the consortium, which operates through the Malian company, Alpha Telecom Mali.\n\n===Asia===\nMonaco Telecom holds a 36.37% stake in Roshan, [[Afghanistan]]'s leading telecommunications