{"title_page": "Callirhoe (mythology)", "text_new": "In [[Greek mythology]], '''Callirrhoe''', '''Callirhoe''' or occasionally '''Kallirroi''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u026ar|o\u028a|i\u02d0}}; [[Ancient Greek]]: \u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03c1\u03c1\u03cc\u03b7 meaning \"beautiful flow\") may refer to the following characters:\n\n* [[Callirrhoe (Oceanid)]], one of the [[Oceanid]] daughters of [[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]], and the mother of [[Geryon]] by [[Chrysaor]].<ref>[[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' 351</ref>\n* Callirhoe, wife of [[Piras (mythology)|Peiras]], son of King [[Argus (king of Argos)|Argus]] of [[Argos]], son of [[Zeus]] and [[Niobe (daughter of Phoroneus)|Niobe]]. She was the mother of [[Argus Panoptes|Argus]], [[Arestor]]ides and [[Triopas]].<ref>Hyginus, ''Fabulae'' 145</ref>\n* Callirhoe, daughter of the river god [[Scamander]], wife of [[Tros (mythology)|Tros]],<ref>[[Tzetzes]] on [[Lycophron]], 29</ref><ref>Scholiast ''on Homer's Iliad'' 20.231 who refers to [[Hellanicus of Lesbos|Hellanicus]] as his authority</ref> and thus, mother of [[Ilus]], [[Assaracus]], [[Ganymede (mythology)|Ganymede]], [[Cleopatra (Greek myth)|Cleopatra]]<ref>[[Bibliotheca (Pseudo-Apollodorus)|Pseudo-Apollodorus]], ''Bibliotheca'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.12.2&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0022 3.12.2]</ref> and possibly, [[Cleomestra]].<ref>[[Dictys Cretensis]], [https://topostext.org/work/152#4.22 ''Trojan War Chronicle'' 4.22]</ref>\n* Callirhoe, daughter of [[Meander (mythology)|Meander]] and consort of [[Car (Greek mythology)|Car]].<ref>[[Stephanus of Byzantium]] s. v. ''Alabanda''</ref>\n* Callirhoe, daughter of [[Nestus]], mother of [[Biston]], [[Odomas]] and [[Edonus]] by [[Ares]].\n* Callirhoe, a maiden who was loved by [[Coresus]].<ref>[[Pausanias (geographer)|Pausanias]], ''Graeciae Descriptio'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+7.21.1&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160 7.21.1]</ref>\n* [[Callirrhoe (daughter of Achelous)|Callirrhoe]], daughter of the river-god [[Achelous]], who betrothed her to [[Alcmaeon (mythology)|Alcmaeon]].<ref>Pseudo-Apollodorus, ''Bibliotheca'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.7&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0022 3.7.6 ff]</ref><ref>Pausanias, ''Graeciae Descriptio'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Paus.+8.24&fromdoc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0160 8.24.8]-10</ref>\n* Callirhoe, daughter of [[Lycus (son of Ares)|Lycus]], king of [[Libya]]. She fell in love with [[Diomedes]] and saved him from being sacrificed to Ares by her father. After Diomedes left Libya, she hanged herself.<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''Parallela minora'' [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A2008.01.0219%3Asection%3D23 23]</ref>\n* Callirhoe, daughter of the [[Boeotia]]n [[Phocus]].<ref>[[Plutarch]], ''Amatoriae Narrationes'' 4</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Portal|Ancient Greece|Myths|}}<references />\n\n==References==\n* [[Gaius Julius Hyginus]], ''Fabulae from The Myths of Hyginus'' translated and edited by Mary Grant. University of Kansas Publications in Humanistic Studies. [https://topostext.org/work/206 Online version at the Topos Text Project.]\n* [[Hesiod]], ''Theogony'' from ''The Homeric Hymns and Homerica'' with an English Translation by Hugh G. Evelyn-White, Cambridge, MA.,Harvard University Press; London, William Heinemann Ltd. 1914. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0130%3Acard%3D1 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library.] [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0129 Greek text available from the same website].\n* [[Plutarch|Lucius Mestrius Plutarchus]], ''Moralia'' with an English Translation by Frank Cole Babbitt. Cambridge, MA. Harvard University Press. London. William Heinemann Ltd. 1936. [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:2008.01.0219 Online version at the Perseus Digital Library.] [http:/